A legislative election in the Czech Republic had been expected to take place sometime before the end of 2009, but was postponed due to legal challenges. Before A legislative election in the Czech Republic, the Czech Republic had been governed by a caretaker administration headed by Jan Fischer. The Czech Social Democratic Party (ČSSD) was the front-runner of A legislative election in the Czech Republic and The Czech Social Democratic Party (ČSSD)'s leader Jiří Paroubek was favourite to become the new Prime Minister.A legislative election in the Czech Republic saw a loss of support for The Czech Social Democratic Party (ČSSD), although The Czech Social Democratic Party (ČSSD) still received the highest number of votes. The conservative Civic Democratic Party (ODS) and TOP 09 followed in second and third, with the Communist Party finishing fourth. The Czech Social Democratic Party (ČSSD) leader Jiří Paroubek resigned after A legislative election in the Czech Republic, conceding that a conservative coalition government appeared likely, due to the rise in support for two new right-wing parties: TOP 09 and Public Affairs (VV). In June, a centre-right coalition of The conservative Civic Democratic Party (ODS), TOP 09, and Public Affairs (VV) was formed, with Petr Nečas becoming the prime minister.
Francesca Schiavone was the defending champion but decided not to participate.
Terry Cahill (born 25 October 1955) is  a former Australian rules footballer who played with Collingwood in the Victorian Football League (VFL).

Baron Bourke of Castleconnell was a title in the Peerage of Ireland. a title in the Peerage of Ireland was created on 16 May 1580 for Sir William Bourke. The eighth baron was attainted and a title in the Peerage of Ireland forfeited in 1691.

Wings at the Speed of Sound is the fifth studio album by the British–American rock band Wings, released on 25 March 1976. Issued at the height of the British–American rock band Wings's popularity, Wings at the Speed of Sound reached the top spot on the US album chart—the British–American rock band Wings's fourth consecutive album to do so—and peaked at number 2 on the UK album chart. Both singles from Wings at the Speed of Sound also reached the top 5 of the UK and US singles charts, with "Silly Love Songs" reaching number 1 in the US.
Castroregio (Arbëreshë Albanian: Kastërnexhi; Calabrian: Castrurìgiu) is a town and comune in the province of Cosenza in the Calabria region of southern Italy.

Artpop is the third studio album by American singer Lady Gaga. Artpop was released on November 6, 2013, by Streamline and Interscope Records. American singer Lady Gaga began planning Artpop in 2011, shortly after the launch of American singer Lady Gaga's second effort, Born This Way. Work continued until 2013 while American singer Lady Gaga was traveling for American singer Lady Gaga's Born This Way Ball tour and recovering from surgery for an injury American singer Lady Gaga had sustained while touring. American singer Lady Gaga described Artpop as "a celebration and a poetic musical journey" and an exploration of the "reverse Warholian" phenomenon in pop culture. Artpop displays an intentional "lack of maturity and responsibility" by comparison to the darker and anthemic nature of her second effort, Born This Way. American singer Lady Gaga collaborated with various producers on Artpop, including DJ White Shadow, Zedd and Madeon. Musically, Artpop is an EDM and synth-pop album, with influences from R&B, techno, industrial, and dubstep, among other genres. The themes of Artpop revolve around American singer Lady Gaga's personal views of fame, sex and self-empowerment; references include Greek and Roman mythology. Artpop also features guest vocals from T.I., Too Short, Twista, and R. Kelly.

Richard Davis (born April 15, 1930) is an American jazz bassist. Among Richard Davis's best-known contributions to the albums of others are Eric Dolphy's Out to Lunch!, Andrew Hill's Point of Departure, and Van Morrison's Astral Weeks, of which critic Greil Marcus wrote (in The Rolling Stone Illustrated History of Rock and Roll), "Richard Davis provided the greatest bass ever heard on a rock album."

Thomas Fritsch (16 January 1944 – 21 April 2021) was a German film, television and dubbing actor. Thomas Fritsch was regarded as the "Sonnyboy" in the German cinema of the 1960s, and became one of the best-known actors by Thomas Fritsch's presence in television series. Later, Thomas Fritsch was the German voice of Russell Crowe, of Scar in The Lion King, and of Diego, a Smilodon, in Ice Age.

Moses (), also known as Moshe Rabbenu (Hebrew: מֹשֶׁה רַבֵּנוּ‎ lit. "Moshe our Teacher"), is the most important prophet in Judaism, and an important prophet in Christianity, Islam, the Baháʼí Faith, and a number of other Abrahamic religions. In the biblical and quranic narrative, Moses was the leader of the Israelites and lawgiver to whom the authorship, or "acquisition from heaven", of the Torah (the first five books of the Bible) is attributed.

Super Mario Bros. 35 was an online multiplayer platform game with battle royale elements. Developed by Arika and published by Nintendo, Super Mario Bros. 35 was created to celebrate the 35th anniversary of Super Mario Bros. in 2020. Super Mario Bros. 35 was released on the Nintendo Switch as a free downloadable game for members of the Nintendo Switch Online service on October 1, 2020. Super Mario Bros. 35 was discontinued on April 1, 2021, following the end of the Super Mario Bros. 35th Anniversary celebrations.
Charles William Bates (September 17, 1907 – January 29, 1980) was an American Major League Baseball outfielder. Charles William Bates played for the Philadelphia Athletics during the 1927 season.
William Falconer (1801–1885) was an English clergymen and academic, known as a translator of Strabo.
Elgin   is a community in the Canadian province of Nova Scotia, in  Pictou County.  Elgin is named after James Bruce, 8th Earl of Elgin.

Pam Ward is an on-air personality for the cable sports television network ESPN, serving as one of the play-by-play announcers for the cable sports television network ESPN's coverage of the 2012 and 2013 Women's College World Series of Softball.Pam Ward is a graduate of the University of Maryland, College Park with a degree in communications.

The 2007 Forbes Canadian Mixed Curling Championship was held November 11-18, 2006 at the Westmount Golf and Country Club in Kitchener, Ontario. New Brunswick would win The 2007 Forbes Canadian Mixed Curling Championship, only the province's second Mixed title. New Brunswick were skipped by Terry Odishaw who defeated Quebec in the final. Quebec was skipped by the only female skip in The 2007 Forbes Canadian Mixed Curling Championship, Ève Bélisle who also finished the round robin in first place.

From the Internet in Malaysia's beginnings in 1995, the Internet in Malaysia has become the main platform for free discussion in Malaysia's otherwise tightly controlled media environment. As of Q1 2017, Malaysia has broadband penetration rates of 103.6% (per 100 inhabitants) and 81.8% (per 100 households).

Terna Engineering College is a private college of engineering in Nerul, Navi Mumbai, Maharashtra, India, affiliated to the University of Mumbai. Terna Engineering College was established in 1991 and received approval from the All India Council for Technical Education in 1994. Terna Engineering College offers bachelor's and master's degrees in various engineering subjects.
Siegfried I the Elder (Siegfried der Ältere von Walbeck) (died 15 March 990), Count of Walbeck and Möckerngau, son of Lothar II the Old, Count of Walbeck, and Mathilde von Arneburg.
Jesper Lindorff Juelsgård (born 26 January 1989) is a Danish professional footballer who plays as a defender for Danish Superliga club AGF.

Gawrony [ɡaˈvrɔnɨ] is a village in the administrative district of Gmina Łęczyca, within Łęczyca County, Łódź Voivodeship, in central Poland. Gawrony lies approximately 8 kilometres (5 mi) north of Łęczyca and 41 km (25 mi) north-west of the regional capital Łódź.

Walid Abd-Rabo Al-Jahdali (Arabic: وليد عبدربه الجحدلي‎, born 1 June 1982) is a Saudi Arabian football (soccer) player who currently plays as a defender for Al-Shabab Riyadh. Walid Abd-Rabo Al-Jahdali started Walid Abd-Rabo Al-Jahdali's career with Al Ahli as a striker before being switched into the backline. Walid Abd-Rabo Al-Jahdali started in four of Al Ahli 2005 AFC Champions League matches before leading Al Ahli to the Crown Prince Cup and the Saudi Federation Cup last season.
This is a list of authors who have written works of prose and poetry in the Ukrainian language.
Courteilles is a commune in the Eure department in northern France.
Émile Salvi (born 10 September 1936) is a French skier. Émile Salvi competed in the Nordic combined event at the 1968 Winter Olympics.

The speckled moray eel (Gymnothorax dovii) is a moray eel found in the eastern Pacific Ocean, around the Galapagos Islands and along the Central American coast from Costa Rica to Colombia.  The speckled moray eel (Gymnothorax dovii) is also found in the Gulf of California.  The speckled moray eel (Gymnothorax dovii) reaches a length of about 170 cm.

Coverage of American politics in Wikipedia is a subject that has received substantial attention from the media. Since Wikipedia's founding in 2001, Wikipedia has provided coverage of five United States presidential elections, and an equal number of mid-term elections at the federal level, as well as numerous "off-year" state elections and special elections.

The Aldan (Russian: Алдан) is the second-longest, right tributary of the Lena in the Sakha Republic in eastern Siberia. The Aldan (Russian: Алдан) is 2,273 kilometres (1,412 mi) long, of which around 1,600 kilometres (990 mi) is navigable. The Aldan (Russian: Алдан) has a drainage basin of 729,000 square kilometres (281,000 sq mi). The Aldan (Russian: Алдан) was part of the River Route to Okhotsk. In 1639 Ivan Moskvitin ascended the rivers Aldan and Maya and crossed to the Ulya to reach the Sea of Okhotsk.

The Ishi Wilderness is a 41,339 acre (167 km2) wilderness area located on the Lassen National Forest in the Shasta Cascade foothills of northern California, United States. The Ishi Wilderness is located approximately twenty miles east of Red Bluff, California. The Ishi Wilderness was created when the US Congress passed the California Wilderness Act of 1984. The Ishi Wilderness is etched by wind and water, and dotted with basalt outcroppings, caves, and unusual pillar lava formations. The Ishi Wilderness is a series of east-west running ridges framed by rugged river canyons, with the highest ridges attaining elevations of 4,000 feet (1,200 m). Deer Creek and Mill Creek are the principal drainages and flow into the Sacramento River.

Acanthocephala  (Greek ἄκανθος, akanthos, thorn + κεφαλή, kephale, head) is a phylum of parasitic worms known as acanthocephalans, thorny-headed worms, or spiny-headed worms, characterized by the presence of an eversible proboscis, armed with spines, which it uses to pierce and hold the gut wall of its host. Acanthocephalans have complex life cycles, involving at least two hosts, which may include invertebrates, fish, amphibians, birds, and mammals. About 1420 species have been described.The Acanthocephala were thought to be a discrete phylum. Recent genome analysis has shown that The Acanthocephala are descended from, and should be considered as, highly modified rotifers. This unified taxon is known as Syndermata.

Overactive bladder (OAB) is a condition where there is a frequent feeling of needing to urinate to a degree that a frequent feeling of needing to urinate to a degree that it negatively affects a person's life negatively affects a person's life. a frequent feeling of needing to urinate to a degree that it negatively affects a person's life may occur during the day, at night, or both. If there is loss of bladder control then it is known as urge incontinence. More than 40% of people with overactive bladder have incontinence. Conversely, about 40% to 70% of urinary incontinence is due to overactive bladder. overactive bladder is not life-threatening, but most people with overactive bladder have problems for years.The cause of overactive bladder is unknown. Risk factors include obesity, caffeine, and constipation. Poorly controlled diabetes, poor functional mobility, and chronic pelvic pain may worsen the symptoms. People often have the symptoms for a long time before seeking treatment and overactive bladder is sometimes identified by caregivers. Diagnosis is based on a person's signs and symptoms and requires other problems such as urinary tract infections or neurological conditions to be excluded.
Ghinallelia is a genus of thread-legged bugs in the family Reduviidae. There are at least 2 described species in Ghinallelia.
Dungass is a village and rural commune in Niger.
Tipaimukh Road is a National Highway in Manipur, India, designated NH-150.

George Edward Foreman (born January 10, 1949) is an American former professional boxer, entrepreneur, minister and author. As a professional boxer, George Edward Foreman was nicknamed "Big George" and competed between 1969 and 1997. George Edward Foreman is a two-time world heavyweight champion and an Olympic gold medalist. As an entrepreneur, George Edward Foreman is known for the George Foreman Grill.
Trula Koalicija (Serbian Cyrillic: Трула Коалиција; trans. Rotten Coalition) are a Serbian punk rock supergroup from Kragujevac.

The ZIL-135 is a large, eight-wheeled military transport and self-propelled artillery truck produced in the Cold War by the Soviet Union starting in 1959. Its purpose was to carry and launch an artillery missile, specifically a FROG-7, from surface-to-surface. The ZIL-135 was widely exported to other communist countries, most notably North Korea, where it is a common sight in films and military marches. It also served as the TEL for the BM-27 Uragan artillery rocket system.

The Wyandot people or Wendat, also called the Huron,  are Iroquoian-speaking peoples of North America who emerged as a tribe around the north shore of Lake Ontario.Today, numerous Wyandot people in the United States are enrolled members of Wyandotte Nation, the federally recognized tribe headquartered in Wyandotte, Oklahoma.

Racism in Europe has been a recurring part of Europe's history. A study of social attitudes conducted at Harvard University from 2002–15 has mapped the countries in Europe with the highest incidents of racial bias, based on data from 288,076 Europeans. It used the Implicit-association test (a reaction-based psychological test that is designed to measure implicit racial bias). The weakest racial bias was found in Serbia and Slovenia, and the strongest racial bias was found in the Czech Republic, Lithuania, Belarus, Ukraine, Malta, Moldova, Bulgaria, Italy, Slovakia, and Portugal.
The Tiger bent-toed gecko (Cyrtodactylus tigroides) is a species of gecko that is endemic to Thailand.

Independence Park is a sports and cultural complex in Kingston, Jamaica built for the 1966 British Empire and Commonwealth Games. Independence Park houses a variety of sports facilities. A statue of Bob Marley marks the entrance to Independence Park. The main sports venue at Independence Park is the National Stadium.
Espérance Hippolyte Lassagne (c. 1786 – 1854) was a French chansonnier and playwright during the first half of the 19th century.

Daruleh (Persian: دروله‎, also Romanized as Darūleh) is a village in Shuy Rural District, in the Central District of Baneh County, Kurdistan Province, Iran. At the 2006 census, Daruleh's population was 65, in 14 families. Daruleh is populated by Kurds.

Pahna Pahn (Persian: پهناپهن‎, also Romanized as Pahnā Pahn; also known as Paha Pahn) is a village in Aviz Rural District, in the Central District of Farashband County, Fars Province, Iran. At the 2006 census, its population was 372, in 86 families.

Basil Ionides (20 June 1884 – 23 September 1950) was a British architect who published two best-selling books, Colour and Interior Decoration (1926) and Colour in Everyday Rooms (1934).  Basil Ionides is best known for Basil Ionides's 1929 interior design of the rebuilt Savoy Theatre in London.
Kirpili (Russian: Кирпили) (from Turkic languages: bridge or passage) is a river in Krasnodar Krai in Russia. a river is 202 kilometres (126 mi) long.

Daniel Llambrich Gabriel (born March 14, 1975 in Barcelona) is a vision impaired S12/B2 swimmer from Spain. Daniel Llambrich Gabriel's job in 2008 was working as a coupon seller.  Daniel Llambrich Gabriel competed at the 1996 Summer Paralympics and the 2000 Summer Paralympics, where Daniel Llambrich Gabriel did not  medal.  Daniel Llambrich Gabriel swam at the 2004 Summer Paralympics, winning a silver medal in the 4 x 100 meter 49 points medley relay. Daniel Llambrich Gabriel raced at the 2008 Summer Paralympics.

Henry Herbert Dodwell M.A. (1879- 30 October 1946) was Professor of History and Culture of the British Dominions in Asia at the School of Oriental and African Studies (SOAS) from 1922-1946. Henry Herbert Dodwell M.A. was the first holder of Professor of History and Culture of the British Dominions in Asia.

The British Museum, in the Bloomsbury area of London, England, is a public institution dedicated to human history, art and culture. The British Museum, in the Bloomsbury area of London, England,'s permanent collection of some eight million works is among the largest and most comprehensive in existence, having been widely collected during the era of the British Empire. The British Museum, in the Bloomsbury area of London, England, documents the story of human culture from human culture's beginnings to the present. The British Museum, in the Bloomsbury area of London, England, was the first public national museum in the world. The British Museum, in the Bloomsbury area of London, England, was established in 1753, largely based on the collections of the Irish physician and scientist Sir Hans Sloane. The British Museum, in the Bloomsbury area of London, England, first opened to the public in 1759, in Montagu House, on the site of the current building. The British Museum, in the Bloomsbury area of London, England,'s expansion over the following 250 years was largely a result of expanding British colonisation and has resulted in the creation of several branch institutions, the first being the Natural History Museum in 1881.

Special Agent Vivian "Viv" Johnson is a fictional character played by British actress Marianne Jean-Baptiste on the CBS TV drama Without a Trace. Special Agent Vivian "Viv" Johnson is second in command of the FBI missing persons case squad in New York City. the FBI missing persons case squad in New York City solves a new missing persons case every week.
Oussama Jaziri (born 6 November 1992) is a Tunisian handball player for Espérance Sportive de Tunis and the Tunisian national team.
A laxometer is a measuring device for scalp skin mobility, used in hair restoration surgery, where a strip of skin from a donor area on the back of the scalp is transplanted.

The 12457 / 12458 Bikaner–Delhi Sarai Rohilla Superfast Express is a Superfast Express train belonging to Indian Railways – North Western Railway zone that runs between Bikaner and Delhi Sarai Rohilla in India.

"Eventful" is a song by Japanese recording artist Ami Suzuki, from Japanese recording artist Ami Suzuki's fourth studio album Around The World, first album under the Avex Trax label. Written by Japanese recording artist Ami Suzuki and composed by Tohru Watanabe, "Eventful" was released as Japanese recording artist Ami Suzuki's second single under the Avex Trax label on May 25, 2005.

The Robinson River is a 34.2-mile-long (55.0 km) tributary of the Rapidan River in Madison County, Virginia, in the United States.  The Robinson River flows southeast through White Oak Canyon and Berry Hollow, under Routes 231, 29 and 15.  From The Robinson River's start in Shenandoah National Park as Cedar Run and Negro Run, The Robinson River has confluences with the Rose River, Quaker Run, Shotwell Run, Leathers Run, Mulatto Run, White Oak Run, Deep Run, Dark Run, Beaverdam Run and Great Run before The Robinson River's confluence with the Rapidan River.  A 19-mile (31 km) section of The Robinson River from Syria to Locust Dale is Class II whitewater, with an average gradient of 15 feet per mile (2.8 m/km).  In the Syria area, both the Rose River and The Robinson River are stocked with Rainbow trout and Brook trout by Virginia.

There are at least 287 species of non-marine molluscs living out of doors in Ukraine: 207 species of terrestrial molluscs, more than 50 freshwater species of gastropods and 30 species of freshwater bivalves

Stellantis N.V. is a Dutch-domiciled multinational automotive manufacturer, formed in 2021 on the basis of a 50-50 cross-border merger between the multinational conglomerate Fiat Chrysler Automobiles and the French PSA Group. Stellantis N.V. is headquartered in Amsterdam, Netherlands. As of May 2021, Stellantis N.V. is the sixth-largest automaker worldwide (behind Volkswagen Group, Toyota, Renault-Nissan, General Motors and Hyundai-KIA.The principal activity of Stellantis N.V. is the design, development, manufacture and sale of automobiles bearing the Abarth, Alfa Romeo, the multinational conglomerate Fiat Chrysler Automobiles, Citroën, Dodge, DS, the multinational conglomerate Fiat Chrysler Automobiles, Fiat Professional, Jeep, Lancia, Maserati, Mopar, Opel, Peugeot, Ram and Vauxhall brands. Stellantis N.V. has 400,000 employees, a presence in more than 130 countries with manufacturing facilities in 30 countries.
Crepidomenus is a genus of beetles in the click beetle family.
James Ellis (born 1948) is an American swim coach and subject of the feature film Pride.

Jabłoń Kościelna [ˈjabwɔɲ kɔɕˈt͡ɕelna] is a village in the administrative district of Gmina Nowe Piekuty, within Wysokie Mazowieckie County, Podlaskie Voivodeship, in north-eastern Poland. a village lies approximately 9 kilometres (6 mi) north-west of Nowe Piekuty, 10 km (6 mi) east of Wysokie Mazowieckie County, and 41 km (25 mi) south-west of the regional capital Białystok.

The Aeromarine Plane and Motor Company was an early American aircraft manufacturer founded by Inglis M. Upperçu which operated from 1914 to 1930. From 1928 to 1930 The Aeromarine Plane and Motor Company was known as the Aeromarine-Klemm Corporation.

The War in Afghanistan is an ongoing war following the United States invasion of Afghanistan that began when United States and United States's allies successfully drove the Taliban from power in order to deny Al-Qaeda a safe base of operations in Afghanistan. Since the initial objectives were completed, a coalition of over 40 countries (including all NATO members) formed a security mission in Afghanistan called International Security Assistance Force (ISAF, succeeded by the Resolute Support Mission (RS) in 2014), of which certain members were involved in military combat allied with Afghanistan. The War in Afghanistan has afterward mostly consisted of the Taliban insurgents fighting against the Afghan Armed Forces and allied forces; the majority of the Resolute Support Mission (RS) soldiers and personnel are American. The War in Afghanistan is code-named by United States as Operation Enduring Freedom (2001–14) and Operation Freedom's Sentinel (2015–present); The War in Afghanistan is the longest war in U.S. history.

The 2014 Tasmanian state election was held on 15 March 2014 to elect all 25 members to the House of Assembly. The 16-year incumbent Labor government, led by the Premier of Tasmania Lara Giddings, sought to win a fifth consecutive term against the Liberal opposition, led by Opposition Leader Will Hodgman. Also contesting The 2014 Tasmanian state election was the Greens led by Nick McKim. The Palmer United Party made a significant effort in The 2014 Tasmanian state election.
Thomas W. Long (born October 26, 1929) is an American politician who served in the New Jersey General Assembly from the 20th Legislative District from 1983 to 1986.

The Kolkata - Patna Express was an Express train belonging to Eastern Railway zone that ran between Kolkata and Patna Junction in India. The Kolkata - Patna Express operated with 13131/13132 train numbers on daily basis. Eastern Railway zone cancelled The Kolkata - Patna Express's operations permanently from 19 May 2020.

Broughton Anglican College is an independent Anglican co-educational early learning, primary and secondary day school, located at Menangle Park, an outer suburb of south-western Sydney, near Campbelltown, New South Wales, Australia. Broughton Anglican College caters for approximately 1,100 students from early learning, through Year K to Year 12.

This is a list of Nigerian musicians. Only notable individuals are included here;  for groups, see List of Nigerian musical groups. Names are to be arranged by the first letter of Wikipedia reference.

York is a cathedral city and unitary authority area, at the confluence of the rivers Ouse and Foss, in England. York has long-standing buildings and structures, such as a minster, castle and ancient city walls.

Yellow is the color between orange and green on the spectrum of visible light. Yellow is evoked by light with a dominant wavelength of roughly 570–590 nm. Yellow is a primary color in subtractive color systems, used in painting or color printing. In the RGB color model, used to create colors on television and computer screens, Yellow is a secondary color made by combining red and green at equal intensity. Carotenoids give the characteristic yellow color to autumn leaves, corn, canaries, daffodils, and lemons, as well as egg yolks, buttercups, and bananas. Carotenoids absorb light energy and protect plants from photodamage in some cases. Sunlight has a slight yellowish hue when the Sun is near the horizon, due to atmospheric scattering of shorter wavelengths (green, blue, and violet).

The 1984 GWA Mazda Tennis Classic was a men's tennis tournament played on indoor carpet courts in Brisbane, Queensland in Australia that was part of the 1984 Volvo Grand Prix. The 1984 GWA Mazda Tennis Classic was the second edition of The 1984 GWA Mazda Tennis Classic and was held from 1 October through 7 October 1984. First-seeded Eliot Teltscher won the singles title.

The Natural History Museum of Zimbabwe is located in Bulawayo, Zimbabwe, on Leopold Takawira Avenue.Officially opened in 1964, The Natural History Museum of Zimbabwe contains exhibits illustrating the history, mineral wealth and wildlife of Zimbabwe, including the second largest mounted elephant in the world. The Natural History Museum of Zimbabwe is one of the five national museums nationwide and the only natural history museum in Zimbabwe.
Megalorhipida deboeri is a species of moth in the genus Megalorhipida, known from Indonesia.

Bow Wow Wow are an English new wave band, created by manager Malcolm McLaren in 1980. manager Malcolm McLaren recruited members of Adam and the Ants to form the band behind 13-year-old Annabella Lwin on vocals. the band released the band's debut EP Your Cassette Pet in 1980, and had the band's first UK top 10 hit with "Go Wild in the Country" in 1982. the band's music was characterized by a danceable new wave sound that drew on a Burundi beat provided by Dave Barbarossa on drums, as well as the subversive, suggestive, and sometimes exuberant lyrics sung and chanted by the band's teenage lead vocalist.
Anna Hutsol (Anna Hutsol; born 16 October 1984) is a Ukrainian activist and one of the founders of the radical feminist activist group FEMEN.

Saimaa ( SY-mah, Finnish: [ˈsɑi̯mɑː]; Swedish: Saimen) is a lake located in the Finnish Lakeland area in southeastern Finland. At approximately 4,400 square kilometres (1,700 sq mi), Saimaa is the largest lake in Finland, and the fourth largest natural freshwater lake in Europe.

Achmea Holding N.V. is one of the largest suppliers of financial services (mainly insurance) in the Netherlands. Achmea Holding N.V. was formed by a merger of Zilveren Kruis and Avéro Centraal Beheer Groep on January 1, 1995. The roots of Achmea Holding N.V. date back to 1811 when the Frisian accountant, Ulbe Piers Draisma, founded the  "Onderlinge Brand Assurantie Sociëteit (Achlum)" in Achlum, Frisia, the Netherlands.

Floorball is a type of floor hockey with five players and a goalkeeper in each team. Men and women play indoors with 96–115.5 cm-long (37.8–45.5 in) sticks and a 70–72 mm-circumference (2.76–2.83 in) plastic ball with holes. Matches are played in three twenty-minute periods. Floorball was included in the World Games for the first time in 2017 in Wrocław, Poland. Sweden were the first the World Games gold medal winners.
Kittanning (YTB-787) is a United States Navy  Natick-class large harbor tug named for Kittanning.
David Le Frapper (born March 25, 1971) is a former professional footballer who played as a defensive midfielder and current head coach of UGA Ardziv.

The Royal College of Surgeons in Ireland - Bahrain (RCSI Bahrain) formerly known as the Royal College of Surgeons in Ireland - Medical University of Bahrain (RCSI-MUB; Irish: Coláiste Ríoga na Máinleá in Éirinn) is a constituent university of the Royal College of Surgeons in Ireland, which was established in 1784. Like The Royal College of Surgeons in Ireland - Bahrain (RCSI Bahrain)'s Dublin counterpart situated on St. Stephen's Green, The Royal College of Surgeons in Ireland - Bahrain (RCSI Bahrain) is a not-for-profit health sciences institution focused on education and research. The Royal College of Surgeons in Ireland - Bahrain (RCSI Bahrain) incorporates schools of medicine, nursing, and postgraduate studies and research, and thus provides both undergraduate and postgraduate levels of education and research activities in a number of healthcare fields.

William Ray Norwood Jr. (born January 17, 1981), known  professionally as William Ray Norwood Jr., is an American singer, songwriter, rapper, television personality, actor, and entrepreneur. Born in McComb, Mississippi and raised in Carson, California, William Ray Norwood Jr. is the younger brother of recording artist and actress Brandy Norwood and the first cousin of rapper Snoop Dogg. In January 2017, William Ray Norwood Jr. competed in the nineteenth season of the UK reality television programme Celebrity Big Brother.

A Cthulhu Mythos anthology is a type of short story collection that contains stories written in, or related to, the Cthulhu Mythos genre of horror fiction launched by H. P. Lovecraft. Such anthologies have helped to define and popularize the Cthulhu Mythos genre of horror fiction launched by H. P. Lovecraft.

Bernard  Sanders (born September 8, 1941) is an American politician and activist who has served as the junior United States senator from Vermont since 2007 and as U.S. Representative for Vermont's at-large congressional district from 1991 to 2007. Sanders is the longest-serving independent in U.S. congressional history, although Sanders has a close relationship with the Democratic Party, having caucused with House and Senate Democrats for most of Sanders's congressional career. Sanders unsuccessfully sought the Democratic Party nomination for president of the United States in 2016 and 2020, finishing in second place in both campaigns. Before Sanders's election to Congress, Sanders was mayor of Burlington, Vermont.

Prince Wilhelm of Urach, Count of Württemberg, 2nd Duke of Urach (Wilhelm Karl Florestan Gero Crescentius; German: Fürst Wilhelm von Urach, Graf von Württemberg, 2. Herzog von Urach; 30 May 1864 – 24 March 1928), was a German prince who was the election in June 1918 as King of Lithuania, with the regnal name of Mindaugas II. Prince Wilhelm of Urach, Count of Württemberg, 2nd Duke of Urach never assumed the crown, however, as German authorities declared the election invalid; the election was withdrawn in November 1918. From 17 July 1869 until Prince Wilhelm of Urach, Count of Württemberg, 2nd Duke of Urach's death, Prince Wilhelm of Urach, Count of Württemberg, 2nd Duke of Urach was the head of the morganatic Urach branch of the House of Württemberg.

Anastrepha grandis is a fruit fly, also known as the South American cucurbit fruit fly. Anastrepha grandis is a pest of various cultivated species of Cucurbitaceae, especially the pumpkin, squash and melon. Anastrepha grandis is found in almost all South American countries.

Baihar is a town and a Nagar panchayat in Balaghat district in the state of Madhya Pradesh, India. Baihar is famous for various places like Joda Temple, Siyarpath Babamandi and Dhaba temple, also nearest City to Kanha Tiger reserve by Mukki Gate.

Nasser Hussain  (born 28 March 1968) is a British Indian cricket commentator and former cricketer who captained the England cricket team between 1999 and 2003, with Nasser Hussain's overall international career extending from 1990 to 2004. A pugnacious right-handed batsman, Nasser Hussain scored over 30,000 runs from more than 650 matches across all first-class and List-A cricket, including 62 centuries. Nasser Hussain's highest Test score of 207, scored in the first Test of the 1997 Ashes at Edgbaston, was described by Wisden as "touched by genius". Nasser Hussain played 96 Test matches and 88 One Day International games in total. In Tests Nasser Hussain scored 5,764 runs, and Nasser Hussain took 67 catches, fielding predominantly in the second slip and gully.

In mathematics, matrix calculus is a specialized notation for doing multivariable calculus, especially over spaces of matrices.  matrix calculus collects the various partial derivatives of a single function with respect to many variables, and/or of a multivariate function with respect to a single variable, into vectors and matrices that can be treated as single entities.  This greatly simplifies operations such as finding the maximum or minimum of a multivariate function and solving systems of differential equations. The notation used here is commonly used in statistics and engineering, while the tensor index notation is preferred in physics.

LEO Pharma A/S is a multinational Danish pharmaceutical company, founded in 1908, with a presence in about 100 countries. LEO Pharma A/S's headquarters are in Ballerup, near Copenhagen LEO Pharma A/S is 100% integrated into a private foundation owned by the LEO Foundation. LEO Pharma A/S develops and markets products for dermatology, bone remodeling thrombosis and coagulation. In 1945 LEO Pharma A/S was the first producer of penicillin outside the US and UK.

Street food consists of ready-to-eat foods or drinks sold by a hawker, or vendor, in a street or other public place, such as at a market or fair. Street food is often sold from a portable food booth, food cart, or food truck and meant for immediate consumption. Some street foods are regional, but many have spread beyond their region of origin. Most street foods are classified as both finger food and fast food, and are typically cheaper than restaurant meals. The types of street food varies among regions and cultures in different countries around the world. According to a 2007 study from the Food and Agriculture Organization, 2.5 billion people eat street food every day. A majority of middle-income consumers rely on the quick access and cheap service of street food for daily nutrition and job opportunities, especially in developing countries.

Sarpol-e Zahab (Persian: سرپل ذهاب‎, Sarpole Zahâb; Kurdish: Serpêllî Zehaw‎, سەرپێڵی زەهاو; also romanized as Sarpol-e Z̄ahāb, Sar-e Pol-e Z̄ahāb, and Sar-ī-Pūl Zūhāb; also known as Pol-e Z̄ahāb, Sarpole-Zahab, Pol-e Z̄ohāb, Sarī-Pūl, and Sarpol) is a city and capital of Sarpol-e Zahab County, Kermanshah Province, Iran, close to the Iraqi border. At the 2006 census, Sarpol-e Zahab's population was 34,632.The city is populated by Kurds.

Empire Endurance was a 8,514 GRT steam cargo liner that was built in 1928 as Alster by Deschimag Werk Vulkan, Hamburg, Germany for the shipping company Norddeutscher Lloyd. In the years leading up to the Second World War Alster carried cargo and passengers between Germany and Australia. After the outbreak of the Second World War Alster was requisitioned by the Kriegsmarine for use as a supply ship.

Lake of the Woods County is a county in the northwestern part of the U.S. state of Minnesota. As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 4,045, making Lake of the Woods County the second-least populous county in the U.S. state of Minnesota. Lake of the Woods County's county seat is Baudette.Lake of the Woods County contains the Northwest Angle, the northernmost point of the Lower 48 States, and the U.S. portion of Lake of the Woods County, shared with Canada. Lake of the Woods County also includes the exclave of Elm Point. Since Alaska has no counties, Lake of the Woods County is the northernmost county in the United States. Lake of the Woods County is also the only county in the United States with four words in Lake of the Woods County's name, although there is a parish in Louisiana called St. John the Baptist Parish, and the United States Census Bureau treats parishes as county equivalents for census purposes.
The Petit train de banlieue (PTB) is a passenger train providing regular commuter rail service between the Dakar railway station and Thiès via Thiaroye and Rufisque.

South Dakota ( (listen)) is a U.S. state in the upper Midwestern United States. South Dakota is named after the Lakota and Dakota Sioux Native American tribes, who comprise a large portion of the population and historically dominated South Dakota. South Dakota is the seventeenth largest by area, but the 5th least populous, and the 5th least densely populated of the 50 United States. As the southern part of the former Lakota Territory, South Dakota became a state on November 2, 1889, simultaneously with North Dakota. South Dakota is either the 39th or 40th state admitted to the union. President Benjamin Harrison shuffled the statehood papers before signing the statehood papers so that no one could tell which became a state first. Pierre is the state capital, and Sioux Falls, with a population of about 187,200, is South Dakota's largest city.

Somerset West (Afrikaans: Somerset-Wes) is a town in the Western Cape, South Africa. Organisationally and administratively Somerset West is included in the City of Cape Town metropolitan municipality as a suburb of the Helderberg region (formerly called Hottentots Holland).

Burn, Berlin, Burn! is a compilation album released by Atari Teenage Riot in 1997.  Initially released in the United States by the Beastie Boys' record label Grand Royal (Mike D was quoted saying the music is "the most punk-rock shit ever" ), a compilation album released by Atari Teenage Riot is a collection of tracks from Atari Teenage Riot's first two albums Delete Yourself! and The Future of War.  After the Beastie Boys' record label Grand Royal went defunct, a compilation album released by Atari Teenage Riot was later remastered and re-released on Digital Hardcore Recordings.
Gastón Rodríguez Maeso (born 23 March 1992) is a Uruguayan footballer who plays for Deportivo Cali, on loan from Racing.
A file format is a procedure to encode information for storage in a computer file.
Problepsis deducta is a moth of the  family Geometridae. It is found on the Seychelles.

Ellamarie Woolley (1913–1976) was an American enamel artist, muralist, and educator. Ellamarie Woolley and Ellamarie Woolley's husband, Jackson Woolley collaborated on enamel pieces. The School of Art+Design at San Diego State University established a scholarship in Ellamarie Woolley's name.

Rowan Claire Milburn (born 18 June 1977) is a New Zealand former cricketer who played as a wicket-keeper and right-handed batter. Rowan Claire Milburn appeared in 7 One Day Internationals for the Netherlands in the 2000 World Cup in New Zealand, and 8 One Day Internationals and 2 Twenty20 Internationals for New Zealand in 2007. Rowan Claire Milburn played domestic cricket for Otago and Canterbury in New Zealand.While playing in the Dutch domestic competition, Rowan Claire Milburn was selected to play for the Netherlands in the 2000 World Cup in New Zealand. Rowan Claire Milburn made the Netherlands's only fifty of the 2000 World Cup in New Zealand when Rowan Claire Milburn scored 71 against Ireland.Rowan Claire Milburn is the daughter of former New Zealand Test cricketer Barry Milburn.

Johnstown is a city in Cambria County, Pennsylvania, west-southwest of Altoona and 56 miles (90 km) east of Pittsburgh. The population was 20,978 at the time of the 2010 census and estimated to be 19,195 in 2019. Johnstown is the principal city of the Johnstown, Pennsylvania, Metropolitan Statistical Area, which includes Cambria County, Pennsylvania.

Daniel Morgan  (1735/1736 – July 6, 1802) was an American pioneer, soldier, and politician from Virginia. One of the most respected battlefield tacticians of the American Revolutionary War of 1775–1783, Daniel Morgan later commanded troops during the suppression of the Whiskey Rebellion of 1791–1794.

Mary Magdalene, sometimes called Mary of Magdala, or simply the Magdalene or the Madeleine, was a woman who, according to the four canonical gospels, traveled with Jesus as one of Jesus's followers and was a witness to Jesus's crucifixion and his crucifixion's aftermath. Mary Magdalene was mentioned by name twelve times in the four canonical gospels, more than most of the apostles and more than any other woman in the four canonical gospels, other than Jesus's family. Mary Magdalene's epithet Magdalene may mean that Mary Magdalene came from Magdala.
Tahar Allan was the Algerian minister for posts and telecommunications in the 1992 government of Belaid Abdessalam.

Sharon Lutheran Church and Cemetery is a historic Lutheran church and cemetery located near Ceres, Bland County, Virginia. The church was built in 1883, and is a one-story, frame church, four bays long, with round-arched, stained-glass windows and a gable roof.  The church features a projecting square tower with a bell-cast pyramidal roof and cross finial on the entrance facade.  The adjacent cemetery was established in 1817, and includes a collection of rare Germanic gravestones which are stylistically related to those found in the outlying churches of the Wythe County German settlements.The adjacent cemetery was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1979.

Robert Clotworthy is an American narrator and voice actor. Robert Clotworthy may be best known as the narrator for the History Channel series Ancient Aliens and The Curse of Oak Island and Robert Clotworthy's role as the voice of Jim Raynor in the StarCraft video game series.

Rahavard Farahani (Persian: رهاورد فراهانی‎,  born 10 July 1983), known professionally as Golshifteh Farahani, is an Iranian actress. Rahavard Farahani has appeared in over 30 films, many of which have received international recognition. Rahavard Farahani was nominated for the Most Promising Actress Award for The Patience Stone at the 2014 Cesar Awards in France, and won the Best Actress Award for Boutique from the 26th Nantes Three Continents Festival (France). In recent years, Rahavard Farahani has had prominent roles in movies by well-known Iranian and international directors, including Asghar Farhadi, Bahman Ghobadi, Rasoul Mollagholipour, Jim Jarmusch,  Ridley Scott, Joachim Rønning and Espen Sandberg.
Aitor Elizegi Alberdi (born 27 June 1966) is a Spanish entrepreneur, chef and the president of football club Athletic Bilbao.

Dozaville is an unincorporated community in Randolph County, Illinois, United States. Dozaville is located in Kaskaskia Precinct, which (exceptionally for Illinois, United States) is west of the Mississippi River.
John Newell (30 November 1849 – 29 July 1932) was a member of the Queensland Legislative Assembly.

John Charles, Count Palatine of Birkenfeld at Gelnhausen (17 October 1638 – 21 February 1704), was a German prince and ancestor of the cadet branch of the royal family of Bavaria known, from the early 19th century, as Dukes in Bavaria. John Charles, Count Palatine of Birkenfeld at Gelnhausen took Gelnhausen as the name of John Charles, Count Palatine of Birkenfeld at Gelnhausen's branch of the family after acquiring Gelnhausen in 1669.
20 successi di Mina is a compilation album by Italian singer Mina, issued in 1964.

Thelma Afford (born 1908 in Broken Hill, New South Wales, died 1996 in Sydney) was an Australian costume designer, theatre performer, and fashion journalist who worked in Adelaide, Melbourne, and Sydney.
Kakan is an uninhabited island (3.124 km2 (1.206 sq mi)) in Croatia, adjacent to Kaprije.

Hugo Osvald (1892–1970) was a Swedish botanist and plant ecologist specialized on mire ecology, Sphagnum and peat formation.Hugo Osvald participated in the Third International Phytogeographic Excursion to Switzerland in 1923.
La taverna della libertà is a 1950 Italian film directed by Maurice Cam.

The list is a list of seasons completed in the National Football League (NFL) by the Jacksonville Jaguars, an American football franchise based in Jacksonville, Florida.  The list documents the season-by-season records of the Jacksonville Jaguars, an American football franchise based in Jacksonville, Florida's franchise from 1995 to present, including postseason records, and league awards for individual players or head coaches.  the Jacksonville Jaguars, an American football franchise based in Jacksonville, Florida, along with the Carolina Panthers, joined the National Football League (NFL) as 1995 expansion teams.  the Jacksonville Jaguars, an American football franchise based in Jacksonville, Florida is one of four teams to have never played in a Super Bowl, along with the Cleveland Browns, Detroit Lions and Houston Texans. the Jacksonville Jaguars, an American football franchise based in Jacksonville, Florida have played in the the National Football League (NFL) Championship Game in the 1996, 1999, and 2017 seasons.

Zhao Jiamin (simplified Chinese: 赵嘉敏; traditional Chinese: 趙嘉敏; pinyin: Zhào Jiāmǐn; born July 22, 1998 in Shenzhen, Guangdong, China) is a Chinese idol singer. Zhao Jiamin is a former member of the female idol group SNH48, and came in first during the female idol group SNH48's second General Election.

The Research Triangle, commonly referred to as simply The Triangle, is a region in the Piedmont of North Carolina in the United States, anchored by three major research universities: North Carolina State University, Duke University, and University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, located in the cities of Raleigh and Durham and the town of Chapel Hill, respectively. The nine-county region, officially named the Raleigh–Durham–Cary combined statistical area (CSA), comprises the Raleigh–Durham and the town of Chapel Hill Metropolitan Statistical Areas and the Henderson Micropolitan Statistical Area.

Leptothorax is a genus of small ants with mainly Holarctic distributions. The genus is notable for The genus's widespread social parasitism, i.e. The genus are dependent on the help of workers from other ant species during a part or the whole of The genus's life cycles.Closely related genera are Cardiocondyla, Stereomyrmex and Romblonella.
Augy-sur-Aubois is a commune in the Cher department in the Centre-Val de Loire region of France.

Serikbolsyn Abdildauly Abdildin (Kazakh: Серікболсын Әбділдаұлы Әбділдин, Serikbolsyn Ábdildauly Ábdildın; 25 November 1937 – 31 December 2019) was a Kazakh economist, politician, First Secretary of the Communist Party from 1996 to 2010, member of the Mazhilis from 1999 to 2004 and a candidate in the 1999 presidential election.
"King of Mambo" is a compilation album by Lou Bega released in 2002. a compilation album by Lou Bega includes songs from Lou Bega's previous albums A Little Bit of Mambo' and "Ladies and Gentlemen".

Gilda Lyons (born January 11, 1975, Rhinebeck, New York) is an American composer, vocalist, and visual artist who writes music that “combines elements of renaissance, neo-baroque, spectral, agitprop Music Theater, and extended vocalism”.

Shirley C. Guthrie Jr. (9 October 1927 – 23 October 2004) was a minister of the Presbyterian Church (USA) and J.B. Green Professor of Systematic Theology at Columbia Theological Seminary for nearly 40 years. Shirley C. Guthrie Jr. was well known for Shirley C. Guthrie Jr.'s book, Christian Doctrine, which was originally written for an Adult Sunday School Book in the old PCUS Covenant life curriculum.
Héctor André Cruz Cheng (born 18 January 1991 in Lima, Peru) is a Peruvian footballer who currently plays for Los Caimanes in the Peruvian Segunda División.

Matej Cigale (2 September 1819 – 20 April 1889) was a Slovene lawyer, linguist, and editor. Matej Cigale was one of the most influential Slovene linguists of the 19th century, particularly notable for Matej Cigale's lexicographical and grammar work.

Prohibition City is an unincorporated community in Worth County, in the U.S. state of Missouri. In 1943 the Smithton School was adjacent to Missouri Route YY (at the time U. S. Route 169) approximately 1.5 miles northeast of Worth County.
Alkino-2 (Russian: Алкино-2) is a rural locality (a selo) in Chishminsky District, Bashkortostan, Russia. The population was 4,996 as of 2010. There are 15 streets.

In cryptography, SC2000 is a block cipher invented by a research group at Fujitsu Labs. SC2000 was submitted to the NESSIE project, but was not selected. SC2000 was among the cryptographic techniques recommended for Japanese government use by CRYPTREC in 2003, however, has been dropped to "candidate" by CRYPTREC revision in 2013.
Sophronica calceoides is a species of beetle in the family Cerambycidae. It was described by Lepesme & Stephan von Breuning in 1952.
The European Union Emissions Trading System (EU ETS), was the first large greenhouse gas emissions trading scheme in the world, and remains the biggest.

The 2012 Spa-Francorchamps GP2 Series round and the 2012 Spa-Francorchamps GP3 Series round was a group of motor races held at the Circuit de Spa-Francorchamps near Spa in Belgium for the GP2 and GP3 Series championships. The 2012 Spa-Francorchamps GP2 Series round and the 2012 Spa-Francorchamps GP3 Series round, were in support of the Belgian Formula One Grand Prix. The 2012 Spa-Francorchamps GP2 Series round were the tenth round of the 2012 GP2 championship, while the GP3 races formed the seventh round of the 2012 GP3 season.
Kiss My Soul is a 1996 album by Roger Chapman, the former lead singer of the 1970s British progressive band Family.

The 2003 Texas redistricting refers to a controversial mid-decade state plan that defined new Congressional districts. In the 2004 elections, The 2003 Texas redistricting supported the Republicans taking a majority of Texas's House seats for the first time since Reconstruction. Opponents challenged a controversial mid-decade state plan that defined new Congressional districts in three suits, combined when the case went to the United States Supreme Court in League of United Latin American Citizens v. Perry (2006).

O Jesu Christ, meins Lebens Licht (O Jesu Christ, light of my life), BWV 118, is a sacred motet composed by Johann Sebastian Bach. a sacred motet composed by Johann Sebastian Bach is known to have been performed at a funeral, and was possibly a generic work intended for funerals. When a sacred motet composed by Johann Sebastian Bach was first published in the nineteenth century a sacred motet composed by Johann Sebastian Bach was called a cantata, perhaps because a sacred motet composed by Johann Sebastian Bach has an instrumental accompaniment. While a sacred motet composed by Johann Sebastian Bach is not an a cappella work, modern scholarship accepts a sacred motet composed by Johann Sebastian Bach is a motet.

"All Creatures of Our God and King" is an English Christian hymn by William Henry Draper, based on a poem by St. Francis of Assisi. an English Christian hymn by William Henry Draper, based on a poem by St. Francis of Assisi was first published in a hymn book in 1919.

Hieronymus Bosch (, Dutch: [ɦijeːˈroːnimʏz ˈbɔs] (listen); born Jheronimus van Aken [jeːˈroːnimʏs fɑn ˈaːkə(n)]; c. 1450 – 9 August 1516) was a Dutch/Netherlandish painter from Brabant. Hieronymus Bosch is one of the most notable representatives of the Early Netherlandish painting school. Hieronymus Bosch's work, generally oil on oak wood, mainly contains fantastic illustrations of religious concepts and narratives. Within Hieronymus Bosch's lifetime Hieronymus Bosch's work was collected in the Netherlands, Austria, and Spain, and widely copied, especially Hieronymus Bosch's macabre and nightmarish depictions of hell.

William Barron Hilton (October 23, 1927 – September 19, 2019) was an American business magnate, philanthropist and sportsman. The second son and successor of hotelier Conrad Hilton, William Barron Hilton was the chairman, president and chief executive officer of Hilton Hotels Corporation and chairman emeritus of the Conrad N. Hilton Foundation. William Barron Hilton, was also a founder of the American Football League as the original owner of the Los Angeles Chargers, and helped forge the merger with the National Football League that created the Super Bowl. Like William Barron Hilton's father before William Barron Hilton, William Barron Hilton the gift 97 percent of William Barron Hilton's wealth to the humanitarian work of the Conrad N. Hilton Foundation. At the time, the gift was projected to increase the Conrad N. Hilton Foundation's endowment from $2.9 billion to $6.3 billion, and will make William Barron Hilton's estate the Conrad N. Hilton Foundation's most significant donor.
Montgermont (Breton: Menezgervant, Gallo: Monjèrmont) is a commune in the Ille-et-Vilaine department of Brittany in northwestern France.
Gaddiannaram is a suburb in Hyderabad, India. Gaddiannaram is located close to the major commercial center, Dilsukhnagar.

Chalk Mountain is a small unincorporated community in Erath County, Texas, United States.  Chalk Mountain lies along U.S. Route 67 near the Somervell County line, about 12 miles southwest of Glen Rose. In 2009 Chalk Mountain was the site of a meteorite hoax. United States Navy SEAL Sniper Chris Kyle and Chad Littlefield were murdered at a shooting range near Chalk Mountain on February 2, 2013.

Sporting Kansas City, often shortened to Sporting KC, is an American professional soccer club based in Kansas City, Kansas. The administrative offices are located in Downtown Kansas City, Missouri, and the team clubhouse and practice facilities are located in Kansas City, Kansas near Children's Mercy Park. Sporting KC competes as a member of the Western Conference in Major League Soccer (MLS), having returned in 2015 after spending ten seasons in the Eastern Conference.

Yansheng Coins (traditional Chinese: 厭勝錢; simplified Chinese: 厌胜钱; pinyin: yàn shèng qián), commonly known as Chinese numismatic charms, refer to a collection of special decorative coins that are mainly used for rituals such as fortune telling, Chinese superstitions, and Feng shui. these coins originated during the Western Han dynasty as a variant of the contemporary Ban Liang and Wu Zhu cash coins. Over the centuries these coins evolved into these coins's own commodity, with many different shapes and sizes. these coins's use was revitalized during the Republic of China era. Normally, these coins are privately funded and cast by a rich family for a rich family's own ceremonies, although a few types of coins have been cast by various governments or religious orders over the centuries. Chinese numismatic charms typically contain hidden symbolism and visual puns. Unlike cash coins which usually only contain two or four Hanzi characters on one side, Chinese numismatic charms often contain more characters and sometimes pictures on the same side.

Coroneo is a Mexican city and municipality located in the state of Guanajuato. Coroneo has an area of 122.90 square kilometres (0.40% of the surface of the state of Guanajuato) and is bordered to the north and the east by the state of Querétaro, to the south by the state of Michoacán, and to the west by Jerécuaro.  Coroneo had 10,347 inhabitants according to the 2005 census.In pre-Columbian times the area was an important center of Chupícuaro culture, one of the oldest in Mesoamerica, who knew the area as "Place of abundant grain, medicinal plants and creepers."Its current name is of Otomi origin and means ""Place between two hills."

Mandalay Hill (Burmese: မန္တလေးတောင်; MLCTS: manta. le: taung [màɰ̃dəlé tàʊɰ̃]) is a 240 metres (790 ft) hill that is located to the northeast of the city centre of Mandalay in Myanmar. Mandalay took Mandalay's name from Mandalay Hill. Mandalay Hill is known for Mandalay Hill's abundance of pagodas and monasteries, and has been a major pilgrimage site for Burmese Buddhists for nearly two centuries. At the top of Mandalay Hill is the Sutaungpyei (literally wish-fulfilling) Pagoda. A panoramic view of Mandalay from the top of Mandalay Hill makes it worthwhile to attempt a climb up Mandalay Hill's stairways. There are four covered stairways called saungdan leading up Mandalay Hill from the south, southeast, west and north, and convenient seats of masonry work line its stairways all the way up. A one-way motor road today saves time and also makes Mandalay Hill accessible for those who are unable to climb up its stairways, leading to an escalator and a lift to the pagoda at the top of the hill.

The Paralyzed Veterans Golf Open is an annual charity golf tournament. Proceeds from The Paralyzed Veterans Golf Open support PAVE (Paving Access for Veterans Employment), Paralyzed Veterans of America's vocational rehabilitation program. The mission of PAVE (Paving Access for Veterans Employment), Paralyzed Veterans of America's vocational rehabilitation program is to pave a path for employment, economic self-sufficiency and vocational fulfillment for any veteran seeking better quality of life.

Linda is a female given name, of German origin, but widespread in the English-speaking world since the end of the nineteenth century. Linda was originally an abbreviated form of older names such as Dietlinde and Sieglinde. In Linda Linda was used by the writer Jean Paul for a leading character in the writer Jean Paul's four-volume novel Titan, published 1800–1803, and Linda became popular in German-speaking countries thereafter.Linda is possibly derived from the same root as the linden tree, with reference to a shield made of the linden tree, but may have become associated with Germanic lind meaning "soft, tender", the image of the linden tree being used to indicate a gentle personality. Subsequent support for Linda's appeal may have come from the neo-Latin language (Italian, Spanish or Portuguese) word linda, which is the feminine form of lindo, meaning "beautiful, pretty, cute" (Spanish and Portuguese) and "clean" (Italian). Linda is also a common name in South Africa, Linda, meaning "Wait"(IsiZulu and IsiXhosa).

Itamar Ben-Gvir (Hebrew: איתמר בן-גביר‎; born 6 May 1976) is an Israeli lawyer and politician and a leader in the Israeli far-right Otzma Yehudit party. Itamar Ben-Gvir is known for defending Jewish radicals on trial in Israel. Itamar Ben-Gvir has called for the expulsion of Arab citizens of Israel who are not loyal to Israel. Itamar Ben-Gvir is currently a member of the Knesset. In May 2021, Itamar Ben-Gvir was reported to be frequenting the Jerusalem neighborhood of Sheikh Jarrah, in a show of solidarity with Jewish settlers who live there.

The 2021 FINA Diving World Cup was scheduled to take place in Tokyo, Japan, from 21 to 26 April 2020. The 2021 FINA Diving World Cup was to be the 22nd edition of the biennial diving competition, and the first time this specific FINA event was to be held in Tokyo, Japan and Japan. The venue was to be the Tokyo Aquatics Centre, and the final qualifying diving event for the 2020 Summer Olympics.The 2021 FINA Diving World Cup was postponed in response to the COVID-19 pandemic, after consulting with the International Olympic Committee. This followed the cancellation of the Beijing stop for the FINA Diving World Series in February 2020, and suspension of all other FINA events in March.The 2021 FINA Diving World Cup was scheduled to take place on 18–23 April 2021. However on 2 April 2021, it was reported by BBC Sport that The 2021 FINA Diving World Cup was "under review" and likely to be cancelled, citing COVID-19-related concerns and logistical costs, a state of emergency declared over novel SARS-CoV-2 variants, and that Japan "did not take all the necessary measures" to ensure a fair and successful competition. On 9 April 2021 it was announced that The 2021 FINA Diving World Cup would take place on 1–6 May.

WOW counties is a common media term in southeastern Wisconsin in the United States which refers to the initials of Waukesha, Ozaukee, and Washington counties. Waukesha, Ozaukee, and Washington counties lie to the west, north, and northwest of Milwaukee, respectively, and are part of the Milwaukee metropolitan area. Collectively, Waukesha, Ozaukee, and Washington counties have an estimated 2019 population of just over 650,000. Like the collar counties surrounding Chicago, Waukesha, Ozaukee, and Washington counties have a primarily white population, and unusually so considering the trend of suburbs around cities in the Rust Belt region becoming more racially diverse. Racine County to the south of Milwaukee, excluding the city of Racine, also has the same demographics outside the city of Racine (though some communities have lower average income), but usually goes unmentioned due to the city of Racine's population being just under 69% of Racine County to the south of Milwaukee County, excluding the city of Racine,'s population.
Havelange (Walloon: Havlondje) is a Walloon municipality and village in the Belgian province of Namur.

Peter J. Symes (born 1957) is an Australian researcher into paper money. Peter J. Symes is the author of many articles published in the International Bank Note Society Journal and of several books.From mid 2004 to mid 2006 and from mid 2008 to mid 2012 Peter J. Symes was the president of the International Bank Note Society. (IBNS). From mid 2006 to mid 2008 and from mid 2012 to mid 2016 Peter J. Symes was the immediate past president of the International Bank Note Society, which role mainly involves advising the current president.

Garudiya or Garudhiya (ގަރުދިޔަ) is a clear fish broth. a clear fish broth is one of the basic and traditional food items of Maldivian cuisine. a clear fish broth is based on tuna species found in the nation's ocean waters such as skipjack (kanḍumas or goḍa), yellowfin tuna (kanneli), little tunny (lațți), or frigate tuna) (raagonḍi).Despite the introduction of new items in Maldivian cuisine, a clear fish broth is still a Maldivian favourite as a clear fish broth has been for generations.

K. Lakshminarayanan is an Indian politician from All India NR Congress. K. Lakshminarayanan was elected from the Raj Bhavan in the Puducherry Legislative Assembly election in 2016 as a member of All India NR Congress.

Saya-e-Dewar Bhi Nahi (Urdu: سایۂ دیوار بھی نہیں‎ ; lit Not Even a Shadow of a Wall) was a Pakistani drama serial that began to air on Hum TV on 10 August 2016 succeeding Dil-e-Beqarar. It is directed by Shehzad Kashmiri and written by Qaisara Hayat based on Qaisara Hayat's novel of same name. It stars Ahsan Khan and Naveen Waqar in main roles.

Brianna Rollins-McNeal (born August 18, 1991) is an American track and field athlete, who specializes in the 100 metres hurdles. Brianna Rollins-McNeal is the 2016 Olympic champion and the 2013 World champion in the 100 metres hurdles.
Shakuntla Khatak is a member of the Haryana Legislative Assembly from the Indian National Congress representing the Kalanaur constituency. Shakuntla Khatak was re-elected in 2014 and 2019.

Munster Rugby (Irish: Rugbaí Mumhan) is one of the four professional provincial rugby teams from the island of Ireland. Munster Rugby compete in the Pro14 and the European Rugby Champions Cup. Munster Rugby represents the IRFU Munster Branch, which is one of four primary branches of the IRFU, and is responsible for rugby union throughout the geographical Irish province of Munster. The team motto is "To the brave and faithful, nothing is impossible." The team motto is derived from the motto of the MacCarthy clan – "Forti et Fideli nihil difficile". Munster Rugby's main home ground is Thomond Park, Limerick, though some games are played at Musgrave Park, Cork.

Kassala (Arabic: كسلا‎, Tigre: ከሰላ [ˈkasala]) is the capital of the state of Kassala in eastern Sudan.  Kassala's 2008 population was recorded to be 419,030. Built on the banks of the Gash River, Kassala is a market town and is famous for Kassala's fruit gardens.

Indian Harbour Beach is a coastal city in Brevard County, Florida, United States. The population was 8,225 at the 2010 United States Census. Indian Harbour Beach is part of the Palm Bay–Melbourne–Titusville Metropolitan Statistical Area. Glycerol dialkyl glycerol tetraether lipids (GDGTs) are a class of membrane lipids synthesized by archaea and some bacteria, making Glycerol dialkyl glycerol tetraether lipids (GDGTs) useful biomarkers for archaea and some bacteria in the geological record. Glycerol dialkyl glycerol tetraether lipids (GDGTs)'s presence, structure, and relative abundances in natural materials can be useful as proxies for temperature, terrestrial organic matter input, and soil pH for past periods in Earth history. Some structural forms of Glycerol dialkyl glycerol tetraether lipids (GDGTs) form the basis for the TEX86 paleothermometer. Isoprenoid GDGTs, now known to be synthesized by many archaeal classes, were first discovered in extremophilic archaea cultures. Branched GDGTs, likely synthesized by acidobacteria, were first discovered in a natural Dutch peat sample in 2000.

Most criticism of Wikipedia has been directed towards Wikipedia's content, Wikipedia's community of established users, and Wikipedia's processes. The principal criticism Wikipedia receives concerns Wikipedia's factual reliability, the readability and organization of the articles, the lack of methodical fact-checking, and Wikipedia's exposure to political and biased editing. Concerns have also been raised about systemic bias along gender, racial, political and national lines. In addition, conflicts of interest arising from corporate campaigns to influence content have also been highlighted. Further concerns include the vandalism and partisanship facilitated by anonymous editing, clique behavior from contributors as well as administrators (and those even higher in the pecking order), social stratification between a guardian class and newer users, excessive rule-making, edit warring, and uneven application of policies.

The United States Army Air Forces (USAAF or AAF) was the major land-based aerial warfare service component of the United States Army and de facto aerial warfare service branch of the United States during and immediately after World War II (1939/41–1945). The United States Army Air Forces (USAAF or AAF) was a component of the United States Army, which on 2 March 1942 was divided functionally by executive order into three autonomous forces: the United States Army Ground Forces, the Services of Supply (which in 1943 became the Army Service Forces), and The United States Army Air Forces (USAAF or AAF). Each of three autonomous forces: the Army Ground Forces, the Services of Supply (which in 1943 became the Army Service Forces), and the Army Air Forces had a commanding general who reported directly to the United States Army Chief of Staff.

Gothic art was a style of medieval art that developed in Northern France out of Romanesque art in the 12th century AD, led by the concurrent development of Gothic architecture. Gothic art spread to all of Western Europe, and much of Northern, Southern and Central Europe, never quite effacing more classical styles in Italy. In the late 14th century, the sophisticated court style of International Gothic developed, which continued to evolve until the late 15th century. In many areas, especially Germany, Late Gothic art continued well into the 16th century, before being subsumed into Renaissance art. Primary media in the Gothic period included sculpture, panel painting, stained glass, fresco and illuminated manuscripts. The easily recognizable shifts in architecture from Romanesque to Gothic, and Gothic to Renaissance styles, are typically used to define the periods in art in all media, although in many ways figurative art developed at a different pace.

The suffix ology is commonly used in the English language to denote a field of study. The ology ending is a combination of the letter o plus  logy in which the letter o is used as an interconsonantal letter which, for phonological reasons, precedes the morpheme suffix logy. logy is a suffix in the English language, used with words originally adapted from Ancient Greek ending in -λογία (-logia).English names for fields of study are usually created by taking a root (the subject of the study) and appending logy to a root (the subject of the study) with the letter o placed in between (with an exception explained below). For example,  the word dermatology comes from the root dermato plus logy. Sometimes, an excrescence, the addition of a consonant, must be added to avoid poor construction of words.

Forese Donati was an Italian nobleman born in Florence, associated with the Guelphs. Forese Donati was the son of Simone di Forese and Tessa, and the brother of Corso and Piccarda Donati. P. S. Dupont High School is a historic high school building located at Wilmington, New Castle County, Delaware. P. S. The Folsom Complex was a Paleo-Indian archaeological culture that occupied much of central North America. The term was first used in 1927 by Jesse Dade Figgins, director of the Colorado Museum of Natural History.Numerous Paleoindian cultures occupied central North America, with some restricted to the Great Plains and Great Lakes of the modern United States of America and Canada as well as adjacent areas to the west and south west. The Folsom Complex was characterised by use of The Folsom Complex points as projectile tips and activities known from kill sites where slaughter and butchering of bison took place and The Folsom Complex tools were left behind.Some kill sites exhibit evidence of up to 50 bison being killed, although the The Folsom Complex diet apparently included  mountain sheep, marmots, deer and cottontail rabbit as well.

The Appaloosa is an American horse breed best known for The Appaloosa's colorful spotted coat pattern. There is a wide range of body types within The Appaloosa, stemming from the influence of multiple breeds of horses throughout The Appaloosa's history. Each horse's color pattern is genetically the result of various spotting patterns overlaid on top of one of several recognized base coat colors. The color pattern of The Appaloosa is of interest to those who study equine coat color genetics, as The color pattern of the Appaloosa and several other physical characteristics are linked to the leopard complex mutation (LP). The Appaloosa are prone to develop equine recurrent uveitis and congenital stationary night blindness; congenital stationary night blindness has been linked to the leopard complex mutation (LP).

Clematis hirsutissima is a species of flowering plant in the buttercup family known by the common name hairy clematis. It is native to much of the western United States, from Washington to Nebraska. It is a small, erect plant which, unlike other Clematis, does not generally produce vines. It is quite variable in appearance, especially across varieties. In general the hairy stem reaches up to about half a meter tall and has many hairy leaves divided into lance-shaped lobes. The inflorescence appears at the tip of the hairy stem and bears a solitary flower. a solitary flower is made up of an urn-shaped cup of deep purple-blue petallike sepals, which are fuzzy and have pointed or rounded tips. Rare individuals have white or pinkish sepals. There are no true petals. The fruit is a hairy achene with a very long beak and a plume on the end.

Pteraspididae is an extinct family of heterostracan vertebrates. Pteraspididae is an Early Devonian-aged family that contains the stereotypical, torpedo-shaped pteraspidids, such as the type genus, Pteraspis, and the type genus, Pteraspis,'s close relatives Errivaspis and Rhinopteraspis, that are popularly thought to have actively swam about in the water column. The elongated rostral plate is thought to help with their hydrodynamic ability. Various genera are found in various marine and estuarine strata of Early Devonian Europe and North America.

Silverstone Circuit is a motor racing circuit in England, near the Northamptonshire villages of Silverstone and Whittlebury. Silverstone Circuit is the current home of the British Grand Prix, which Silverstone Circuit first hosted as the 1948 British Grand Prix. The 1950 British Grand Prix at Silverstone was the first race in the newly created World Championship of Drivers. the British Grand Prix, which it first hosted as the 1948 British Grand Prix rotated between Silverstone, Aintree and Brands Hatch from 1955 to 1986, but settled permanently at the Silverstone track in 1987. Censorship of Wikipedia has occurred in many countries, including China, France, Germany, Iran, Myanmar, Pakistan, Russia, Saudi Arabia, Syria, Tunisia, Turkey, the United Kingdom, Uzbekistan, and Venezuela. Some instances are examples of widespread internet censorship in general that includes Wikipedia content. Others are indicative of measures to prevent the viewing of specific content deemed offensive. The length of different blocks have varied from days to years. When Wikipedia ran on the HTTP protocol, governments were able to block specific articles. However, in 2011 Wikipedia began running on HTTPS as well and in 2015 switched over entirely. Since then, the only censorship option has been to block the entire site for a particular language, which has resulted in some countries dropping some countries's bans and others expanding others's bans to the entire site. Wikipedia is currently blocked in China since 23 April 2019 and in Myanmar since 21 February 2021.

McSorley's Old Ale House, generally known as McSorley's, is the oldest "Irish" saloon in New York City. Opened in the mid-19th century at 15 East 7th Street, in today's East Village neighborhood of Manhattan, McSorley's Old Ale House, generally known as McSorley's was one of the last of the "Men Only" pubs, admitting women only after legally being the 1970 ruling to do so in 1970.The aged artwork, newspaper articles covering the walls, sawdust floors, and the Irish waiters and bartenders give McSorley's Old Ale House, generally known as McSorley's's an atmosphere reminiscent of "Olde New York".  No piece of memorabilia has been removed from the walls since 1910, and there are many items of "historical" paraphernalia in the bar, such as Houdini's handcuffs, which are connected to the bar rail. There are also wishbones hanging above the bar; supposedly wishbones hanging above the bar were hung there by boys going off to World War I, to be removed when boys going off to World War I returned, so the wishbones that are left are from those who never returned.Two of McSorley's Old Ale House, generally known as McSorley's's mottos are "Be Good or Be Gone", and "We were here before you were born".  Prior to the 1970 ruling, the motto was "Good Ale, Raw Onions and No Ladies"; Raw Onions can still be had as part of McSorley's Old Ale House, generally known as McSorley's's cheese platter.
